  "The Rank-Nullity Theorem states that for an m x n matrix A, rank(A) + nullity(A) = n, where n is the number of columns. Rank is the number of pivots, and nullity is the number of free variables.": "",
  "What is a 'staircase pattern' in the context of REF?": "",
  "A repeating pattern in the columns": "",
  "A pattern where entries alternate between positive and negative": "",
  "The arrangement of zeros on the main diagonal": "",
  "The descending diagonal pattern formed by pivot positions moving right and down through the matrix": "",
  "The staircase pattern describes how each successive pivot is located further to the right (and lower in the matrix) than the one above, creating a step-like visual pattern.": "",
  "What does 'nullity' of a matrix refer to?": "",
  "The number of free variables, which equals the dimension of the null space": "",
  "The determinant of the matrix": "",
  "The number of rows minus the number of columns": "",
  "The number of zero entries in the matrix": "",
  "The nullity of a matrix is the dimension of its null space (the set of solutions to Ax = 0), which equals the number of non-pivot columns (free variables) in the REF.": "",
  "What is the difference between REF and RREF?": "",
  "REF requires pivots to be 1, while RREF does not": "",
  "There is no difference; they are the same form": "",
  "REF applies only to square matrices, while RREF applies to all matrices": "",
  "RREF additionally requires each pivot to be 1 and the only nonzero entry in its column": "",
  "REF requires zeros below each pivot with the staircase pattern. RREF adds two more requirements: all pivots must be 1, and all entries above each pivot must also be zero.": "",
  "What does 'consistent' mean for a linear system after examining its REF?": "",
  "The REF contains no row of the form [0 0 ... 0 | c] where c is nonzero": "",
  "The coefficient matrix is square": "",
  "The number of pivots equals the number of unknowns": "",
  "All variables can be solved for uniquely": "",
  "A system is consistent if it has at least one solution. In the REF of the augmented matrix, this means there is no row [0, 0, ..., 0 | c] with c nonzero, which would represent the impossible equation 0 = c.": "",
